          "body": "The word *kipher* (atonement) appears in the chapter's final two verses — the same root that governs the Day of Atonement legislation in Leviticus 16 and the entire sacrificial logic of the book. Its placement here is deliberate: the entire forty- or eighty-day structure of purification culminates not in the passage of time, but in atonement. The priest makes atonement; then she is clean. Time prepares; atonement resolves. The New Testament author of Hebrews places Leviticus's entire atonement system in explicit typological relationship to the sacrifice of Christ (Hebrews 9:11-14; 10:1-14). The *chattaah* of Leviticus 12 is one thread in that vast fabric. Every lamb brought to the tent doorway, every pair of turtledoves offered by mothers who could afford no more, pointed forward to the One whose blood does not merely maintain covenant access for an interval — but cleanses the conscience once for all (Hebrews 9:14) and opens the way into the holy of holies without the barrier of impurity ever again (Hebrews 10:19-22)."
