        "excerpt": "On the eighth day the flesh of his foreskin shall be circumcised.",
        "body": "Verse 3 interrupts the purity legislation with a single sentence about the male child: on the eighth day, he is circumcised. The placement is structurally arresting. The mother is in the middle of her seven-day uncleanness; the child's covenant-entry rite is performed during that period. The juxtaposition is not accidental — it places the sign of the Abrahamic covenant (Genesis 17:9-14) within the uncleanness window, before the mother has been restored to the sanctuary.\n\nThe eighth day is theologically rich. In Levitical legislation, eight marks the day after the completion of a full week — the first day of a new sequence. Newly ordained priests complete their ordination on the eighth day (Lev. 9:1); skin-disease sufferers are re-examined on the eighth day (Lev. 14:10, 23); bodily-discharge sufferers offer on the eighth day (Lev. 15:14, 29). The eighth day is Leviticus's day of new beginning. That circumcision falls on the eighth day signals that the male child's entry into the covenant is an act of new creation — the cutting away of the flesh that marks him as belonging to the God of Israel.\n\nThe practical implication within chapter 12 is that the child's covenant standing precedes the mother's restored access to the sanctuary. The circumcision happens on day eight; the mother's forty-day period does not conclude until day forty. Israel's males are formally enrolled in the covenant before their mothers are restored to full priestly access — a structural fact the text states but does not comment on. Paul's argument in Galatians 3-4 about circumcision and the Abrahamic promise, and his identification of baptism as the covenant sign that replaces circumcision in Christ (Colossians 2:11-12), gives the church its New Testament interpretive frame: the eighth-day rite was always a sign pointing to a greater cutting-away and a deeper new beginning.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mul* (circumcise) is the same root used in Genesis 17:11, the Abrahamic covenant command, and in Joshua 5:2-9, the circumcision at Gilgal before the conquest. *Basar orlah* (flesh of the foreskin) — the physical location of the covenant sign. *Shemini* (eighth) appears repeatedly in Leviticus as the marker of new-beginning-after-completion."
