        "excerpt": "But if she bears a female child, then she shall be unclean for two weeks, as in her menstruation; and she shall remain in the blood of her purification for sixty-six days.",
        "body": "The chapter's most discussed feature is its asymmetry: the birth of a son generates seven days of *niddah*-uncleanness and thirty-three days of purification-blood (forty total); the birth of a daughter generates fourteen days of *niddah*-uncleanness and sixty-six days of purification-blood (eighty total). The text states the law without explanation. This absence of rationale has generated centuries of interpretive effort.\n\nAncient interpreters, including Josephus (*Antiquities* 3.11.3) and the rabbis of the Mishnah (*Niddah* 3:7), proposed that a girl child is herself in a state of *niddah* from birth, generating her mother's doubled uncleanness. Patristic interpreters, including Origen, read typological significance into the numbers themselves. Modern scholars are more cautious: Jacob Milgrom (*Leviticus 1-16*, Anchor Bible, 1991) surveys the proposals and concludes that no fully satisfying explanation has been offered. Milgrom himself suggests that the doubling may reflect ancient Near Eastern medical observation about postpartum recovery differences — an explanation that contextualizes without fully resolving the asymmetry.\n\nWhat the text makes clear is the two-phase structure that applies in both cases: an initial period of acute uncleanness parallel to *niddah* (phase one), followed by a longer period of purification-blood during which the woman is not in the acute *niddah* state but remains restricted from contact with consecrated things and from entering the sanctuary (phase two). The two phases are distinct: phase one is a state of impurity; phase two is a transitional, protected state in which the woman's body completes its postpartum process under divinely-governed temporal management. The theological import: God does not demand instant restoration. He prescribes a process, a duration, a pace — and at the end of that process, He provides the means of full restoration through the priest.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tohorah* (purification, cleanness) — the noun from *taher*. The 'blood of her purification' is not blood that makes her clean; it is blood that marks the period during which she is in the transitional purification-state. *Niddah* (menstruation, separation) anchors both phases to the established purity-law of Leviticus 15."
