        "excerpt": "She shall bring to the priest at the doorway of the tent of meeting a one year old lamb for a burnt offering and a young pigeon or a turtledove for a sin offering. Then he shall offer it before the Lord and make atonement for her, and she shall be cleansed.",
        "body": "When the days of her purification are completed — and not before — the woman comes to the priest at the doorway of the tent of meeting. The location is precisely the liminal space where the human and the divine meet in Leviticus: not inside the sanctuary (she has been excluded from it), but at its threshold. The priest officiates between the woman and the presence of God, receiving her offering and presenting it before the LORD.\n\nTwo offerings are required. The burnt offering (*olah*) — a one-year-old lamb — is wholly consumed on the altar. In Leviticus 1, the burnt offering is the worshiper's expression of total consecration and devotion; it ascends entirely to God. The sin offering (*chattaah*) — a young pigeon or turtledove — addresses the impurity-state the woman has been in. John E. Hartley (*Leviticus*, WBC, 1992) argues persuasively that the *chattaah* in ritual-impurity contexts functions as a 'purification offering' whose blood de-contaminates what the impurity has affected — including the sanctuary itself, which has been at risk of impurity by proximity to the community. Together, the two offerings address both dimensions: the positive (consecration, worship, renewed devotion) and the negative (the impurity-state, the barrier to the holy).\n\nThe priest's role is not ceremonial formality. He 'makes atonement' (*kipher*) — the same verbal root that governs the Day of Atonement in Leviticus 16. *Kipher* is the theological heart of the Levitical system: to cover, to ransom, to satisfy the requirement that separates the impure from the holy. The result is not merely social re-entry but priestly declaration of cleanness (*taher*). She is not self-declared clean; she is declared clean by the representative of God, on the basis of an offering accepted before the LORD. This structure — offering, atonement, declaration of cleanness — is the micro-pattern of what the sacrificial system as a whole was doing for Israel across centuries, pointing toward the offering that would make atonement once for all (Hebrews 10:10-14).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kipher* (atonement, cover) — the same root as *kapporeth*, the mercy seat of the ark (Exodus 25:17-22). *Qarav* (present, bring near) — the standard Levitical verb for presenting offerings before the LORD. *Taher* (clean, pure) — the goal the entire chapter has been moving toward; its occurrence at the end of both v. 7 and v. 8 forms the chapter's double resolution."
