        "body": "Verse 8 is brief, but its canonical echo is immense. The graduated sacrifice provision — two birds in place of the lamb for those who 'cannot afford' it — appears here and nowhere else in the Pentateuch's explicit legislation for a specific ritual occasion. It represents a consistent Levitical pastoral principle: God's holiness is not the possession of the wealthy. Atonement is accessible to every Israelite, regardless of economic capacity, because what makes the offering effective is not the price of the animal but the priestly act before the LORD.\n\nLuke 2:22-24 identifies Mary's offering at the Jerusalem temple as precisely 'a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons, in accordance with what is said in the Law of the Lord.' Luke is citing Leviticus 12:8 directly — the poverty provision. The theological weight is staggering: the mother of the Son of God was among the poor of Israel. The family that raised the Messiah could not afford the standard lamb. Jesus of Nazareth entered the world not merely subject to the law (Galatians 4:4) but embedded in its specific provisions for the economically marginalized. His mother's offering was the offering of those who had nothing to bring but the minimum the law permitted.\n\nThis does not mean poverty is a spiritual virtue or that Luke is making a class-polemic. It means that the Son who would become the final *kipher* — the one atonement that renders all Levitical atoning acts complete (Hebrews 9:26-28) — entered His redemptive mission through the door of Israel's mercy provision. Every element of Leviticus 12 that surrounded His birth — the eighth-day circumcision (Luke 2:21; Lev. 12:3), the forty-day purification (Luke 2:22; Lev. 12:4), the poverty offering (Luke 2:24; Lev. 12:8) — was a shadow whose substance is the One who stood in its place. As Charles Spurgeon observed, 'the law is the Gospel in shadow; the Gospel is the law in substance.' Leviticus 12:8 is one place where that shadow is sharp enough to see a face."
